		title: "L'Amande",
		description:
			"L'Amande is an Italian cosmetics brand. \"In the nineteenth century L'Amande was one of the main brands of the ancient Marseilles soap making \"Garcin & Rabattu\". The growing importance that the brand gradually assumed and the great appreciation on the part of the clientele meant that in 1884 it was registered at the Chamber of Commerce of Marseille and even gave its name to the company: thus was born the \"Huilerie & Savonnerie de L'Amande\" , destined to become one of the most important soap factories of the golden age of Marseille soap making (late 19th century, early 20th century).\nDuring the important expansion phase of the 1950s L'Amande crossed the Alps, becoming an Italian in all respects, along with other minor brands of the FISAM (Italian Factory of the Savonnerie Amande of Marseille) of Vallecrosia in the province of Imperia, a company set up around 30 years earlier from the Huilerie & Savonnerie of L'Amande specifically to produce and market their soaps in Italy and Colonies. Meanwhile in Marseille, also due to the heavy losses caused by the bombings of the Second World War, the Huilerie & Savonnerie de L'Amande ceased its activity. All of its original formulations, machinery and customers finally passed to the company L'Amande Srl based in Savona.\nThis history, our history, so ancient and so rooted in the territory, that strip of land bathed by the Mediterranean Sea between Genoa and Marseille is now part of ourselves and our products. For this reason we use only the best oils, perfumes and essences of our land, with specific olfactory and phytocosmetic virtues: olive oil, real Mediterranean gold and sweet almond oil from which our brand took its name; the broom, the strawberry tree, the typical blackberry plants of the Mediterranean maquis; the honeysuckle and the hawthorn that perfume the country lanes adorning the typical dry stone walls; the pitosforo now an integral part of the landscape of the Riviera and many others.\nPerfumes and sensations of a land where the sea breeze blends with the warm, sometimes flowery notes, sometimes more decidedly fruity than a generous Nature in every season, where plants, aromatic herbs and flowers invade paths, hills and even cliffs.\" - a note from the brand.\nDesigner L'Amande has 17 perfumes in our fragrance encyclopedia. Trademarks and logos belong to respected companies and manufacturers and are used solely to identify products and companies.",
