			'Samuel Timothy "Tim" McGraw is an American country singer and actor, married to singer Faith Hill. From his debut in the early \'90s, he had a lot of success and became the most popular male singer in country music. He published several multi-platinum albums with his characteristic sound - commercial country, updated honky tonk, country-rock and contemporary ballads.\nThe singer was born and raised in Louisiana. After studying sports medicine he decided to dedicate to music and went to perform and sing in Nashville clubs for a couple of years. His first album was published in 1993.\nMcGraw\'s breakthrough hit from was Not a Moment Too Soon, known as "Indian Outlaw", in 1994. It reached the country Top Ten and even crossed over to the pop Top 20. This album was selling over five million copies and topping both the country and pop album charts; it was also the best-selling country album of the year.\nIn 1996, McGraw supported the album with an extensive tour, accompanied by opening act Faith Hill. After the tour was over, McGraw and Hill married, in a union of country star power followed by the media. McGraw\'s next album, 1997\'s Everywhere, featured a McGraw-Hill duet called "It\'s Your Love,". The second duet by the couple was"Just to Hear You Say That You Love Me," released in 1998.\nWith the multi-platinum success of Everywhere, McGraw was poised to take over Brooks\' throne as the king of contemporary country. In 1999 he launched triple-platinum A Place in the Sun, hit number one country and pop. 2000 brought McGraw\'s first Grammy, for Best Country Vocal Collaboration - duet from Hill\'s Breathe album, "Let\'s Make Love."\nA great hit was his 2001 album Set This Circus Down, giving him four more number ones on charts! The Tim McGraw album was released in late 2002, and it also featured a faithful cover of Elton John\'s "Tiny Dancer." McGraw kept the formula the same on 2004 album Live Like You Were Dying, utilizing his road band, as well as co-mixing/producing the record himself. Let It Go followed in 2007, with Southern Voice arriving in 2009. McGraw had a major role in the film Country Strong which was released in 2011. The singer’s latest album is Emotional Traffic, which was finally issued in January of 2012.\nThe singer has also launched two perfumes for men – McGraw and Southern Blend. McGraw by Tim McGraw is a fragrance for men presented as the first perfume by country singer Tim McGraw. The perfume was launched in 2008 in collaboration with Coty and constructed as a woody-spicy fragrance. It opens with bergamot with nutmeg, while a heart is opulent and juicy with lavender wrapped with moss and Artemisia. Base notes finish with amber, patchouli, sandalwood and tonka, decorated with intoxicating aromas of whiskey.\nCoty Beauty and Tim McGraw presented another fragrance in 2009, named Southern Blend. Tim McGraw\'s wish was not to name this fragrance in French style (just like his first edition, Tim McGraw), but to make it an approachable, everyday fragrance, strong and charming. Southern Blend incorporates essences of man from the South, who is masculine, charismatic, strong, but also sexy and tough in the same time. This composition includes grapefruit, star annis, bergamot, lavender, violet leaf, whiskey, vetiver, amber and tobacco. Perfumer of this edition is Richard Herpin of Firmenich.\nDesigner Tim McGraw has 7 perfumes in our fragrance base. Tim McGraw is a new fragrance brand. The earliest edition was created in 2008 and the newest is from 2013. Tim McGraw fragrances were made in collaboration with perfumers Coty and Richard Herpin.',
